tem than the STS. I always liked the engine-less plane, expendable but cheap &amp; reliable engines, and easy Shuttle-C type modifiaction.<br>
<br>
 I disagree with the many &amp; various comments detracting from the validity of the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.orbital.com/LaunchVehicle/SpacePlane/">OSP</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->/ <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.astronautix.com/craft/hl20.htm">HL-20</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->/<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.astronautix.com/craft/hl42.htm">42</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> concepts.<br>
 The article talks nonsense as if on escape/abort, the OSP will just <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">fall free</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> of a malfunctioning booster (&quot;telescoping down into an inferno&quot; or some such, in a pad fire, the plane falls right down, or the jettisonned booster accelerating up into the rear end of the plane as the plane boosts away at 8G).<br>
 Read the HL-20/42 articles, and get back to us (note the 8G+ escape motors and RTLS sustainers). Consider development times/costs, given that the HL-20 is well worked out already, and if you're making wishes, then it can be streamlined and done much more efficiently than completely redesigning our entire STS infrastructure. (how does a top-mounted OSP put side/torque loads on the stack? The wings/lifting body?)<br>
<br>
I'll even go along with minimally redesigned current ELVs as the booster for the OSP instead of a completely new RLV as a prerequisite. Throw away the boosters every time, and we still have crewed access safe &amp; cheaper than the Shuttle.<br>
Given that the launch mass of the HL-20 is ~13 tons, and the HL-42 is ~30 tons, that gives us a complete replacement for everything the Shuttle does for us now, vastly cheaper than the Shuttle. Put a bit of work eventually into RLV stages for the same planes, and we're even better off. The STS or Energia/Buran stacks work fine for near-term HLVs.<br>
 Get the space program back into doing useful work, and worry about where we should be in 2020 as we go along (fully reusable, safe &amp; robust 1STO HTOHL planes or whatever dream machine we want).<br>
<br>
I'm all for scrapping the curent Shuttle designs. Much of what the articles spoke of makes sense, but they'e talking nonsense about the OSP/PLS concepts.<br>
<br>
